Given the root of a binary tree, determine if it is a valid binary search tree (BST).

A valid BST is defined as follows:

The left subtree of a node contains only nodes with keys strictly less than the node's key.
The right subtree of a node contains only nodes with keys strictly greater than the node's key.
Both the left and right subtrees must also be binary search trees.


 In BST left < root<right, so inorder traversal give us exactly the same thing, but for this we use a points that holds a previous value, if previous value if greater then previous then
 Binary Search Tree is not valid return false, else true;



 ##Algorithm
 1. Use inorder traversal: left -> root -> right.

2. Keep a variable prev to store the previously visited value.

3. Start with prev = null.

4. During inorder traversal:
   a. Recursively validate the left subtree.
   b. Compare current node value with prev.
   c. If prev is not null and current value <= prev, return false.
   d. Update prev = current node value.
   e. Recursively validate the right subtree.

5. If the entire traversal finishes without violation, return true.



solution 
class Solution {

    // This stores the previously visited node value during inorder traversal.
    // We use Integer instead of int because we want to allow null at the beginning.
    public Integer prev;

    public boolean isValidBST(TreeNode root) {

        // Before starting traversal, no previous value exists.
        prev = null;

        // Start inorder traversal and return whether the tree is valid.
        return inOrder(root);
    }

    private boolean inOrder(TreeNode root) {

        // If current node is null, it is valid.
        // Empty subtree is always considered valid.
        if (root == null) return true;

        // First, check the left subtree.
        // If left subtree is invalid, immediately return false.
        if (!inOrder(root.left)) return false;

        // Now we are visiting the current node.
        // In inorder traversal of a BST, current value must be greater than previous value.
        // If current value is less than or equal to previous value, it is not a valid BST.
        if (prev != null && root.val <= prev) return false;

        // Update prev to current node value.
        // This current node becomes the previous node for the next visited node.
        prev = root.val;

        // Finally, check the right subtree.
        return inOrder(root.right);
    }
}
